05433nam a22008535i 9780231551908DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020004401  a97802315519087 a10.7312/scot196942doi  a(DE-B1597)566408  a(OCoLC)1198931567  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aD16.9b.S427 2020 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a9012231 aScott, Joan Wallach, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn the Judgment of History /cJoan Wallach Scott. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRuth Benedict Book Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: History, Race, Nation -- t1. The Nation- State as the Telos of History: Nuremberg, 1946 -- t2. The Limits of Forgiveness: South Africa’s Truth and Reconciliation Commission, 1996 -- t3. Calling History to Account: The Movement for Reparations for Slavery in the United States -- tEpilogue: Revisioning History -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the face of conflict and despair, we often console ourselves by saying that history will be the judge. Today’s oppressors may escape being held responsible for their crimes, but the future will condemn them. Those who stand up for progressive values are on the right side of history. As ideas once condemned to the dustbin of history—white supremacy, hypernationalism, even fascism—return to the world, threatening democratic institutions and values, can we still hold out hope that history will render its verdict?Joan Wallach Scott critically examines the belief that history will redeem us, revealing the implicit politics of appeals to the judgment of history. She argues that the notion of a linear, ever-improving direction of history hides the persistence of power structures and hinders the pursuit of alternative futures. This vision of necessary progress perpetuates the assumption that the nation-state is the culmination of history and the ultimate source for rectifying injustice. Scott considers the Nuremberg Tribunal and South Africa’s Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which claimed to carry out history’s judgment on Nazism and apartheid, and contrasts them with the movement for reparations for slavery in the United States. Advocates for reparations call into question a national history that has long ignored enslavement and its racist legacies. Only by this kind of critical questioning of the place of the nation-state as the final source of history’s judgment, this book shows, can we open up room for radically different conceptions of justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHistoriography. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aNationalismxHistory. 0aNuremberg Trial of Major German War Criminals, Nuremberg, Germany, 1945-1946xHistory. 0aRacismxHistory. 0aReparations for historical injusticeszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020z9783110704648oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/scot1969440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231551908423Coveruhttps://www.degruyt